        <p>National programs and websites are a starting point, but the most practical help for day-to-day single-parent life often exists at the community level — and it's harder to find. This page focuses on how to locate local resources rather than listing national ones you may not qualify for or that don't exist near you.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>Start with 211.</strong> Dial or text <strong>211</strong> from any phone in the U.S. It's a free, confidential social services hotline staffed by people who know what's available in your area — food, housing, childcare, financial help, legal aid. More useful than most search engines for local resources.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Finding resources by zip code</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>211.org</strong> — the web version of the 211 hotline. Search by zip code and category. <a href="https://www.211.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">211.org</a></li>
          <li><strong>findhelp.org</strong> — searches local nonprofit and government programs by zip code and need. One of the most comprehensive local resource finders available. <a href="https://www.findhelp.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">findhelp.org</a></li>
          <li><strong>benefits.gov</strong> — federal benefits screener that shows what you may qualify for. <a href="https://www.benefits.gov/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">benefits.gov</a></li>
          <li><strong>Google "[your city/county] single parent resources"</strong> — often surfaces local nonprofits and programs that aren't in national directories.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Food banks and pantries</h2>
        <p>Food banks serve anyone who needs them — no proof of income required at most locations, and you don't need to explain yourself. Many operate as monthly or weekly "shopping" experiences rather than handout lines.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Feeding America food bank locator</strong> — find your nearest food bank. <a href="https://www.feedingamerica.org/find-your-local-foodbank" target="_blank" rel="noopener">feedingamerica.org/find-your-local-foodbank</a></li>
          <li><strong>Local church pantries</strong> — many churches run weekly food pantries open to the community regardless of membership. Search "[your city] church food pantry" or ask at 211.</li>
          <li><strong>Little Free Pantries</strong> — community pantry boxes (like Little Free Libraries) in many neighborhoods. Search <a href="https://littlefreepantry.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">littlefreepantry.org</a> for one near you.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Community centers</h2>
        <p>Community centers are one of the most underused resources for single parents. Many offer:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Low-cost or free childcare and after-school programs</li>
          <li>Youth sports leagues and activities</li>
          <li>Classes and workshops for parents</li>
          <li>Meeting space for support groups</li>
          <li>Computer and internet access</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Look for: YMCA/YWCA, Boys &amp; Girls Clubs, community recreation centers (often run by parks departments), and neighborhood community centers.</p>

        <h2>Faith-based organizations</h2>
        <p>Regardless of your own beliefs, faith communities often run some of the most accessible family support programs in a given area — and most are open to everyone, no membership or faith required.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Meals and food assistance</li>
          <li>After-school programs and tutoring</li>
          <li>Counseling and support groups (including divorce support — DivorceCare runs through many churches)</li>
          <li>Emergency financial assistance (utility bills, rent)</li>
          <li>Social connection for both you and your kids</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Call local congregations and ask directly what programs they offer to the community. Many don't advertise widely.</p>

        <h2>Fatherhood programs</h2>
        <p>Federally-funded fatherhood programs exist in most counties and offer resources specifically for dads — co-parenting support, job training, legal navigation, and peer connection.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Search "[your county] fatherhood program" or ask at 211</li>
          <li>Many are run through county Health and Human Services departments</li>
          <li>Some are court-connected and may be required in custody cases; others are voluntary and open to any dad</li>
          <li>National Fatherhood Initiative maintains a program directory at <a href="https://www.fatherhood.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">fatherhood.org</a></li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Libraries</h2>
        <p>Public libraries are significantly more useful than most people realize:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Free activities and programming for kids year-round</li>
          <li>Free internet and computer access</li>
          <li>Free access to databases, job boards, and learning resources</li>
          <li>Many host social services office hours — a social worker or benefits counselor on-site once a week</li>
          <li>Meeting space for community groups</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Emergency help</h2>
        <p>If you're in a short-term crisis — can't cover rent, utilities, or food this month — these are the fastest paths:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Call 211</strong> — they know what's available in your area this week, including emergency funds that may not be listed online</li>
          <li><strong>Salvation Army</strong> — emergency financial assistance in most U.S. cities. <a href="https://www.salvationarmyusa.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">salvationarmyusa.org</a></li>
          <li><strong>Catholic Charities</strong> — open to everyone regardless of faith. Emergency assistance programs in most dioceses. <a href="https://www.catholiccharitiesusa.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">catholiccharitiesusa.org</a></li>
          <li><strong>St. Vincent de Paul Society</strong> — local chapters provide emergency financial help for utilities, rent, and food. Search "[your city] St. Vincent de Paul."</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>Ask directly and ask often.</strong> Local resources are poorly advertised by design — they're funded to help people in need, not to run marketing campaigns. The best way to find them is to call 211, walk into a community center, or ask someone at your child's school. Resources that seem obscure are often just not Googleable.</p>
        </div>
